6,http://www.armslist.com/posts/2502006,For Sale:  Original Marlin 39 with octagon barrel,"North of Madison, Madison, Wisconsin",$ 350,"Listed On: Friday, May 16, 2014",Rifles,Marlin                                                                                ,22 Long Rifle                                                                                ,Lever Action                                                                                ,Rifle,"We have here a slightly neglected 1920's marlin 39. Rifle was improperly stored for over 40 years, which caused the corrosion on the end of the barrel. Sight bead is damaged from corrosion also. Corrosion was touched up by gunsmith without my knowledge when I dropped it off for a minor repair (lever spring). Wood was most likely refinished at some point. There was a scope mounted to the top of the barrel a long time ago. Mounting holes were drilled through the marlin script. Not much here for a collector, but if your looking for cheap nostalgia this is it. Shoots standard velocity .22 ammo. Local sale only. No shipping.
Price is firm. Possible trade for sbc performance parts."

The Star Model PD is a compact and lightweight semi-automatic pistol which was manufactured from 1975 to 1990 by the firearms manufacturing company Star Bonifacio Echeverria, S.A., located in the city of Eibar in the Basque region of Spain.[1]

The Model PD can be loaded with six .45 ACP pistol cartridges in the detachable internal magazine, plus one in the chamber, and was very popular with police and civilian users in the self-defense and backup gun role, especially in the United States.

The Star PD improved on its predecessor (Star Model PKM) by using a low-profile adjustable rear sight and by removing material from the slide and other small changes. These modifications, combined with its aluminum alloy construction, resulted in a slim, compact, lightweight and relatively powerful pistol, revolutionary for the time. As it also bore an external resemblance to the well-known M1911 pistol, the gun sold very well in the U.S. until it was replaced in 1990 by the Firestar M45."

530,http://www.armslist.com/posts/2502530,For Sale:  Walther Olympia Pistole,"Appleton, West Side, Wisconsin, United States","$ 1,500","Listed On: Sunday, December 29, 2013",Handguns,Walther                                                                                ,no type,no type,Pistol,"Walther ""Olympia Pistole"". This is a semi-auto pistol chambered in 22 KURZ (short), this is the rapid fire model. These pistols were made for and used in the 1936 Olympic Games, where the Germans dominated the small bore pistol events. The Olympia Pistole has a 7.4 inch barrel, alloy slide, the frame is drilled and tapped for under frame weights, wood grips. All the serial numbers match on the frame, slide, and magazine. There is also a leather holster that comes with the gun. The holster has a German name on, but it is very tough to read. The story that I have been told is that this pistol was carried by a German Officer, and at some point was taken from him. I am unable to confirm if this pistol was used in the 1936 Games or not. All the records from Walther were destroyed during the war. I can tell you that the winner of the 1936 Olympic games 25 meter rapid fire event used a Walther Olympia Pistole, rapid fire model. This model of pistol was made from 1936-1940.
I do have more pictures then what are on the website here, please contact me with any questions or to request the other pictures please let me know."
